# Context Window Management — Don't Guess, Confirm

## The problem this solves

When a codebase gets large, agents start hallucinating — inventing function names, assuming imports exist, referencing files they have never read. They also silently degrade mid-task when their context fills up, producing worse output without telling you. This rule stops both.

---

## Before starting any task on a large codebase

- Read only the files directly relevant to the task — not the entire project
- Do not reference a function, component, or variable unless you have seen it in a file you actually read
- If you are unsure something exists — say so, search for it, then continue

```
CONTEXT PLAN
────────────
Files I need to read for this task: [list — be specific]
Files I will NOT read unless needed: [everything else]
What I already know without reading: [only things stated in this conversation]
```

---

## When you hit uncertainty mid-task

Stop and say this explicitly — do not guess:

```
UNCERTAINTY FLAG
────────────────
I am not certain [X] exists in this codebase.
I need to check [specific file or directory] before continuing.
Proceeding without checking would risk [describe the failure mode].
```

Then check. Never proceed on an assumption when you can verify.

---

## Summarise before continuing long tasks

After every major section of a long task, output this before moving on:

```
PROGRESS CHECKPOINT
───────────────────
Completed: [what is done]
Remaining: [what is left]
Assumptions made so far: [anything assumed without verifying]
Files not yet read that may be relevant: [list]
Risk of proceeding: LOW / MEDIUM / HIGH
```

If risk is HIGH — stop and ask before continuing.

---

## When hitting context limit mid-task — Save State and Hand Off

This is the part no other rule covers. When you feel context degrading — responses getting vague, earlier decisions being forgotten, uncertainty increasing — do not push through. Stop and hand off cleanly.

Output this before stopping:

```
CONTEXT HANDOFF
───────────────
Task: [original task in one sentence]
Status: [what percentage is done]
Completed steps: [bullet list of exactly what was done]
Remaining steps: [bullet list of exactly what is left]
Decisions made: [every non-obvious choice made so far and why]
Files modified: [list every file touched and what changed]
Files still needed: [list files the next session needs to read]
Next action: [the exact first thing the next session should do]
Watch out for: [anything that could go wrong in the remaining steps]
```

Then stop. Do not attempt to finish a task you cannot hold in context. A clean handoff is always better than a hallucinated completion.

---

## Hard rules

- [ ] Never reference a function you have not seen in the actual code
- [ ] Never assume a file exists — check with a directory listing first
- [ ] Never silently continue when context is degrading — flag it
- [ ] Never complete a handoff without listing every decision made so far
- [ ] Always read the handoff note at the start of a new session before touching anything

---

## The rule in one line

Uncertainty is not a reason to guess — it is a reason to stop and check. Context limits are not a reason to push through — they are a reason to hand off cleanly.
